<!-- Begin center content table -->
<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" summary="center content table">
    <tr>       
        <!-- begin center text area -->
        <td valign="top" colspan="3">
            <div id="header">
                 <span id="HEcontentheader" class="HEheader">Savouring the Health Benefits of Chocolate</span>
            </div>
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="512">
            
            <div id="articlebox">
                <span class="HEbox" id="pageContent">If you love the taste of chocolate you are not alone!&nbsp; Chocolate often “tops the lists” of favourite foods each year.&nbsp; In fact, the International Cocoa Organization (ICCO) estimates that Canadians consume 3.90 kg of chocolate each year on a per capita basis.&nbsp; <BR><BR><IMG height=175 src="/Images/HE_chocolate.jpg" width=117><BR><BR>Taste has always been one of the reasons behind our love affair with chocolate. Another reason that might surprise you is the potential health benefits it may bring. For instance, some recent scientific evidence suggests that chocolate, especially dark chocolate, may play a role in heart health and improvements to our mood.&nbsp; <BR><BR>However, chocolate can contain large amounts of fat and sugar, so consuming chocolate in smaller amounts makes sense. Generally, enjoying chocolate is one case where “a little bit goes a long way.”&nbsp; <BR><BR>Finding the right balance is the key to enjoying both the taste and health benefits of chocolate. Think quality over quantity and you can savour the flavour without overdoing it! <BR><BR><STRONG>Understanding Possible Health Benefits of Chocolate<BR></STRONG>Interest in the health benefits of chocolate has grown in recent years.&nbsp; The scientific evidence that has been collected so far suggests that chocolate may indeed offer health benefits.&nbsp; 
<BR>However, it is important to keep in mind that there is still a great deal to be learned about the potential health benefits of chocolate.&nbsp; At this point, chocolate appears to play a role in promoting heart health and enhancing our moods or feelings, in part because of its unique ingredients.<BR><BR>[new]<BR><U><EM>Heart Health <BR></U></EM>Although a common food, chocolate actually contains a number of very complex compounds that can affect how our bodies function. 
<UL>
<LI>For example, chocolate, especially dark chocolate, is a rich source of compounds known as flavonoids.&nbsp; Flavonoids, which are also found in vegetables and fruits, help to protect our cells from damage.&nbsp; Recent nutrition research suggests that the flavonoids found in chocolate may help to keep the cells in our hearts healthy and lower our risk for conditions such as heart disease, high blood pressure and stroke.</LI></UL>
<P><EM><U>Mood<BR></U></EM>Chocolate can also influence our mood, something that may explain our fascination with this food.</P>
<UL>
<LI>In addition to flavonoids, chocolate also contains a compound called phenylethylamine (PEA).&nbsp; PEA can create unique feelings of alertness or focus – a sensation that some describe as mimicking the feelings we get when we fall in love!&nbsp;&nbsp; Caffeine, in relatively small amounts, is also found in chocolate and may enhance the sensations that PEA creates</LI></UL>
<P><EM><U>Not all Chocolate is Equal!<BR></U></EM>Not all chocolate is equal when it comes to the amount of flavonoids and PEA you receive.<BR>&nbsp; <BR>Chocolate comes from cocoa beans which have been gone through a variety of processes in order to transform them into the chocolate we enjoy.</P>
<UL>
<LI>For example, after harvesting, the cocoa beans are fermented, and roasted to enhance their flavour.&nbsp; Unfortunately, these treatments can break down the healthy ingredients in chocolate. In general, the more of this kind of processing that a chocolate undergoes, the lower the flavonoid and PEA content will be. </LI>
<LI>Dark chocolate and cocoa powder are the least processed forms of chocolate. As a result, they have the highest levels of flavonoids and PEA, and are most likely to offer the potential health benefits that have been linked to chocolate.&nbsp;</LI></UL>
<P>In contrast to dark chocolate, milk chocolate and so-called “white chocolate,” (which is not technically a form of chocolate at all) undergo a great deal more processing. This additional processing decreases the amount of flavonoids and PEA found in these products which, in turn, reduces the potential health benefits you might get from eating them. <BR><BR>[new]<BR><STRONG>Keeping it Healthy: Consume Chocolate in Moderation <BR></STRONG>Chocolate comes from cocoa beans which are naturally rich in saturated fats.&nbsp; It is this fat that helps to give chocolate its creamy texture and rich taste.&nbsp; In addition, fat is sometimes added to chocolate products during processing.&nbsp; All in all, this means that chocolate is a high source of fat and calories.&nbsp; <BR><BR>It is also important for chocolate lovers to consider the amount of sugar that comes with chocolate.&nbsp; On its own, chocolate has a strong, bitter flavour.&nbsp; That’s one reason why sugar is added to chocolate during processing to improve the taste.&nbsp; This added sugar also adds calories. <BR><BR>Given these factors about fat and sugar content, it’s wisest to consume chocolate in moderation. <BR><BR><STRONG>Healthy Eating Tips <BR></STRONG>Use the following tips to help you savour the flavour of chocolate, while maintaining a healthy, balanced diet:</P>
<UL>
<LI>When buying chocolate products, aim to choose dark chocolate or cocoa most of the time. These forms of chocolate normally contain at least 70% cocoa solids; this information will be found on the product label.</LI>
<LI>Use cocoa rather than chocolate when baking or making chocolate-flavoured drinks.&nbsp; Cocoa offers a strong chocolate taste but is lower in fat, calories and sugar than chocolate.&nbsp; In addition, cocoa is reasonably priced and can be stored in a dark cupboard for up to one year, qualities that make it an appealing choice. </LI>
<LI>Keep portion sizes small.&nbsp; Limit the amount of chocolate you eat to no more than 30 grams (1 oz) per day.&nbsp; By sticking to small portions you can reap the potential health benefits chocolate may offer without taking in unwanted fat and sugar. </LI>
<LI>Go for quality over quantity.&nbsp; If you know you’re prone to over-doing it with chocolate, don’t keep large amounts in your home.&nbsp; Instead, purchase a small amount of high quality chocolate as a special treat.&nbsp; Savour the flavour of a single dark chocolate truffle when a craving strikes, rather than eating a handful of chocolate chip cookies every day.&nbsp;</LI></UL>
<P>Common sense is the key to reaping any health benefits chocolate has to offer.&nbsp; Satisfy your sweet-tooth by choosing small portions of dark chocolate or cocoa, and balance these indulgences with a variety of nutrient-rich foods, such as vegetables and fruits.&nbsp;<BR>&nbsp;<BR>[endpage]<BR><STRONG>Learn More<BR></STRONG><A href="http://www.dietitians.ca/Nutrition-Resources-A-Z/Fact-Sheet-Pages(HTML)/Anti-oxidants/Pleasures-of-Healthy-Eating--Chocolate,-Green-Tea,.aspx " target=\_blank\>The Pleasures of Healthy Eating:&nbsp; Exploring the Health Benefits of Chocolate, Green Tea and Red Wine <BR></A>Online article from the Dietitians of Canada.<BR><BR><A href="http://www.eatrightontario.ca/en/ViewDocument.aspx?id=281" target=\_blank\>For the love of chocolate</A>&nbsp;<BR>Online article from Eatright Ontario.&nbsp; <BR></P></span>
            </div>
            <!-- end center text area -->
        </td>
                
